2. How constants are discovered

Mathematical constants usually appear when we ask questions like:
	•	what is the invariant of this structure?
	•	what ratio never changes?
	•	what limit does this sequence approach?

Examples:

π comes from

\frac{\text{circumference}}{\text{diameter}}

e comes from

\lim_{n\to\infty}(1+\frac{1}{n})^n

φ comes from

\frac{a+b}{a} = \frac{a}{b}

Constants are therefore limits or invariants of processes.

⸻

3. Can we invent new constants?

Yes—but usually by discovering new structures.

Examples of ways constants arise:

limits of sequences

Example:

\lim_{n\to\infty} f(n)

geometric invariants

ratios that remain constant under transformation.

dynamical systems

attractor constants (like Feigenbaum).

integrals

areas or probabilities that produce irrational numbers.

In fact, mathematicians regularly define new constants this way.

⸻

4. Example of a hypothetical new constant

Suppose we define:

“average curvature of randomly generated polygons approaching a circle.”

The limit of that process would converge to some value.

That value would become a new mathematical constant.

So constants are not invented arbitrarily; they appear when structures stabilize under limits.

